      "role": "user",
      "content": "ok that makes sense for the social/political side. but i also need to cover the more \"logical\" or \"economic\" arguments people used back then. like, what were the actual arguments for how segregation or redlining might have been \"good\" for urban stability or protecting property values? i want to understand the specific logic they used to claim it was a functional necessity for cities.",
