      "content": "i see. so the core of that argument was basically that homogeneity leads to better economic outcomes and less crime. can you expand on that part a bit? specifically, if we're looking at it from that era's perspective, how did they justify the idea that certain races were 'naturally' more inclined toward disorder compared to others? i'm trying to get the specific way they framed those racial differences as a factual basis for policy.",
